<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence Submitted by the NFFO</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">to the management of designated sites </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">should be capable of showing when it is necessary and appropriate to apply precaution, whilst also enabling proportionate management to occur</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> within a risk based and adaptive management regime</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Consideration should be given to collaborative and voluntary approaches, avoiding or minimising the negative effects of displacement of existing activities, and identifying mitigation options to be adopted in order to permit fishery access, whilst meeting conservation objectives.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">When selecting</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> additional MCZs</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> greater emphasis needs to be given to achieving synergistic outcomes between</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">conservation and sustainable marine use</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  This may be assisted through spatial analyses that help to optimise site selection and the consideration of co-location possibilities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">A process of designing and consulting on management measures should be concluded prior to site designation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Areas where fishing is already restricted should be recognised as contributing to biodiversity protection alongside any MPA network.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The NFFO is the representative body for fishermen in England, Wales and Northern Ireland.  Member vessels range from 110 metre pelagic freezer trawlers operating in international waters to small, under 10 metre vessels, beach launched and with limited range.  The Federation holds seats on the North Sea, North West Waters, Pelagic and Long Distance Regional Advisory Councils.  The NFFO is also a member of Europeche, the European trade federation for the fishing industry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We welcome the opportunity to provide evidence to the inquiry launched by the Environmental Audit Committee on Marine Protected Areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We support the government’s decision to take a more careful approach through the application of appropriate levels of evidence in order to justify MCZ site designation.  It is our view that the initial process of site selection undertaken by the 4 English regional projects suffered on account of the following:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">An unrealistic planning timeframe given the limited evidence available to support the process and the need to take careful and considered decisions through wide stakeholder engagement based on that evidence base.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">An absence of consideration in the scientific selection guidance of the consequences of displacing existing human activities to other areas in terms of the net ecological outcomes that may accrue.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">A stakeholder engagement process tilted towards broad interest groups, which inevitably constrained engagement and the influence of those whose marine livelihoods depend upon the decisions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Lack of coherence with other marine planning jurisdictions, particularly acute in the Irish Sea, for example.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Against this background, we offer the following on the topics of examination of the Environmental Audit Committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Designated Sites</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We consider that a collaborative and evidence-based approach to the designation and management of MCZs is the preferred option, both in terms of achieving ecological objectives and minimising socio-economic disruption.  Towards this end, we support a risk-based approach to delivering management measures, which considers precaution with respect to vulnerable, rare and fragile marine features that face impending threat.  However, for the majority of areas selected for MPAs which are intended to contribute to a representative network of features rather than the suite of vulnerable, rare or fragile features, a precautionary approach is less justified.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Many sites selected where bottom trawl fisheries occur on sediment habitats that are subject high levels of natural disturbance from wave and storm action that mask the effects of trawling.  Given also that fisheries are often an ongoing rather than a new activity, there is less justification for knee-jerk, precautionary management without appropriate evidence.  Such an approach would neglect a managed transition and lead to maximum economic impact for highly uncertain gain and would be contrary to the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">modus operandi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> in so many other areas of public policy.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">to management </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">be capable of showing when it is necessary and appropriate to apply precaution, whilst also enabling proportionate management to occur.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We do, however, recognise that there is unlikely to be perfect levels of evidence in any case and therefore there is also the need to make trade-offs between precaution, evidence and proportionality.  Recognising this, we support an adaptive approach to management that seeks to identify consensual management arrangements with an emphasis on ongoing evidence gathering and scientific assessment in order to inform the performance of measures.  Over time, measures may then be adjusted according to the growing evidence base. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In addition, the following should also be considered when designing management measures: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The scope for applying voluntary measures</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Such approaches obviate the need for overly burdensome regulation, and can minimise the costs to business through the introduction of choice and in transitioning to a new management regime. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Dependent upon the particular circumstances of the site, examples might include the following elements:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Identifying the outcomes of management (e.g. net reduction of physical pressure) and allowing marine users to develop a management plan to meet those outcomes (results-based management).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Providing choices in the selection of mitigation approaches to reducing a particular pressure.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Adopting a voluntary code of conduct with respect to gear use / spatial management measures.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Voluntary validation/verification of operations within a site.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The displacement of existing activities in terms of economic impacts and also to avoid unintended negative ecological consequences.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">With respect to fishing activities, consideration should be given to mitigation measures that enable fisheries to adapt where possible rather than face prohibition.  Little emphasis has yet to be placed on conducting the requisite technical work in order to incorporate such considerations into assessments employed to inform management measures. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Enabling resource users to contribute to monitoring and scientific research, which can provide a form of mitigation to those businesses adversely affected by site management, promote collaboration and buy-in to measures and management objectives and provide scientific research outputs at lower cost.  This would also help to underpin an adaptive management regime.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Planning for Additional </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">MCZs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Applying Evidence </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The principle of best available evidence </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">applied at the outset of the English MCZ selection process as an application of the precautionary principle to environmental management.  It is predetermined on the idea that failure to take timely action would result in serious environmental loss, and therefore the lowering of the usual standards of evidence to public policy decision-making can be justified.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.99pt; padding-left:2.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We have argued above with respect to management measures w</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">hy such an approach should </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">a limited role to play.  In so far as completing the selection of sites is concerned, working to deliver a network in a non-alarmist and careful manner will likely produce a much more robust network that best promotes conservation and sustainable marine livelihoods.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The MCZ selection process to date has already demonstrated the importance of having appropriate levels of evidence.  Without it, it is impossible to effectively inform likely management measures that should be applied at a site</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> and therefore inform what the social, economic and displacement consequence could be.  A premature designation process that lacks appropriate levels of evidence could result in assigning unreliable site conservation objectives and risk the application of inappropriate or disproportionate management measures.  Such circumstances unnecessarily pressurises the whole process of developing the network which risks leading ultimately to unintended and perverse outcomes occurring not only by unduly impacting upon for marine users, but also in terms of delivering conservation gains for the wider marine environment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Moreover, given that designation leads to duties on the responsible authorities, the new dimension to this issue is the increasingly toxic atmosphere in which some of the more litigious NGOs use the courts, or threat of legal action, to force those authorities to follow the letter of the law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">For this reason we have come to the conclusion that it is unsafe to designate MCZs until the process of designing and consulting on appropriate management measures has been completed.  This is the only way that we can be assured that designation will not trigger a sequence of events that lead to inappropriate and premature management measures being applied.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Displacement </span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The scientific principles applied to the selection of sites under the English regional projects were purely concerned with natural environmental considerations. They did not consider the fundamental challenge for sustainable marine planning – how to maximise the scope for synergistic outcomes for conservation and sustainable marine use.  In so far as sustainable fisheries are concerned, a failure to achieve this would be manifested through fisheries displacement that:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">shifts</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">fishing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">effort onto more pristine habitat.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">eads the fleet to expend additional effort in catching equivalent quantities of fish.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">oncentrates effort that leads to local depletions and reduces the sustainable yield obtain</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">able from the fishery resource.  This is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">a particular risk </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">where proposals have been selected for mud habitats located on high yielding </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">nephrops</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (Dublin bay prawn)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> fisheries </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">(particularly in the Irish Sea) due to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> their limited and highly defined extent.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We consider that such risks should be assessed methodically, and include the application of spatial analyses that combine fisheries</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> and other </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">marine use data with habitat vulnerability </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">data so that such unintended consequences are avoided and sites are optimally selected</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Marine plannin</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">g</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">It is our view that a more conducive approach to network design, taking into account both evidence </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">and displacement considerations</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> would have better materialised through the marine planning system.  It would also likely be achieved at lower cost to the UK tax payer given that a single planning process would be delivered.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">As well as more effectively addressing the issue of displacement and the application of evidence, such a process would likely be more capable of assessing whether it is desirable to co-locate particular features with particular marine uses, and evaluate the selection of features when taking into account social, economic and displacement factors. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">process of site selection</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> would also benefit from a more coherent approach </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">taking account of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> all planning areas within a particular sea area.  This is particularly relevant in the Irish Sea given the multiple planning jurisdictions that exist.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Scale of ambition</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">When accounting for the scale of the MPA network, little consideration has so far been given to the extent to which measures are already in place which limit access to fisheries. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There is a plethora of areas in UK waters where fishing is restricted, including areas where all fishing is prohibited.  Such areas make a contribution to biodiversity and there is a need to take account of such areas alongside any formal MPA network.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>